  "text": "Microscopy has been traditionally used to identify Baylisascaris spp. based on adult morphological characters although some species can be difficult to distinguish, especially if only immature worms are found. However, because of the similarity among the [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Studies have also characterized the genetic diversity, investigated the population structure and the phylogenetic relationships among Baylisascaris species, which is important for understanding the zoonotic potential and host specificity of these parasites. To discuss the phylogenetic relationships among the Baylisascaris spp. that occur in the New World in a broader context, this section includes data published on Baylisascaris spp. from Asia and Europe and Baylisascaris procyonis from raccoons.",
